[{"id":"VR914679","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\"><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows a diagram of unpolarized ultraviolet light passing through a polarizing filter in a straight path. The unpolarized ultraviolet light has intensity equals I sub 1, and enters the polarizing filter, which is oriented horizontally. The light that exits the polarizing filter has intensity equals I sub 2.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR914679.g01.svg\"/></div></div></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Unpolarized ultraviolet light with intensity <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"I sub 1\"><math alttext=\"I sub 1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math></span></span> is incident on one side of a polarizing filter, as shown in the figure. The ultraviolet beam that is transmitted through the polarizer has intensity <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"I sub 2\"><math alttext=\"I sub 2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></span></span>, which is either less than <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"I sub 1\"><math alttext=\"I sub 1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math></span></span> or equal to <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"I sub 1\"><math alttext=\"I sub 1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math></span></span>. How does <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"I sub 2\"><math alttext=\"I sub 2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></span></span> compare to <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"I sub 1\"><math alttext=\"I sub 1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math></span></span>, and what evidence or reasoning supports the claim? Assume that intensity losses at the polarizing filter, if any, are due only to polarization effects.</p>\n","rubricRef":"VR914679_rubric","choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"I sub 2\"><math alttext=\"I sub 2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></span></span> is less than <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"I sub 1\"><math alttext=\"I sub 1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math></span></span>. Ultraviolet light is a longitudinal wave and can be polarized.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"I sub 2\"><math alttext=\"I sub 2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></span></span> is less than <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"I sub 1\"><math alttext=\"I sub 1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math></span></span>. Ultraviolet light is a transverse wave and can be polarized.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"I sub 2\"><math alttext=\"I sub 2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></span></span> is equal to <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"I sub 1\"><math alttext=\"I sub 1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math></span></span>. Ultraviolet light is a longitudinal wave and cannot be polarized.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"I sub 2\"><math alttext=\"I sub 2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></span></span> is equal to <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"I sub 1\"><math alttext=\"I sub 1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math></span></span>. Ultraviolet light is a transverse wave and cannot be polarized.</p>"],"answer":1}]